##Key concepts:
FTP (File Transfer Protocol): An old, dedicated client-server protocol used to transfer files over a network. It transmits files and login credentials in plain, unencrypted text.

P2P (Peer-to-Peer Applications): Distributed software architectures (like BitTorrent) used for direct file sharing across multiple independent hosts.

##Cybersecurity Relevance
Credential Sniffing: Because standard FTP lacks encryption, anyone sitting on the same Wi-Fi or network path can easily read the username and password out of the air using basic tools.

Data Exfiltration: Attackers who break into a company network look for FTP access or run P2P tools to quickly upload gigabytes of sensitive stolen files to external servers.

##Tools
Wireshark: Used to read raw FTP passwords right out of intercepted network traffic.

Hydra: A tool used to brute-force crack FTP login passwords by guessing thousands of combinations per minute.

##Blue Team (Defenders)
Process: Defenders completely ban standard FTP in corporate environments, replacing it with SFTP (Secure FTP) which encrypts the connection. They block P2P file-sharing protocols at the firewall level to ensure sensitive corporate files cannot be shared out to public networks.

End Goal: To prevent authentication theft and stop unauthorized data transmission.

##Red Team (Attackers)
Process: Attackers scan networks for legacy FTP servers. If found, they run automated password-guessing tools to compromise them, or sniff the network wires waiting for a legitimate admin to log in, stealing their credentials in plain text.

End Goal: To gain an easy foothold on a system or steal corporate data assets.
